    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-02-25T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-02-25T10:00:00-05:00" n="731"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d731">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.00/565: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-02-25T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >February 25, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 25—3:56 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>64. In the course of a brief conversation today Litvinov<note n="15"
                        xml:id="d731fn15">Maxim Litvinov, Soviet Commissar for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> expressed some surprise and great satisfaction at the
                    results of the Japanese elections. He said that he believed the victory of the
                    Minseito Party indicated that the sentiment of the Japanese people was clearly
                    against the policy of military adventures and that he now expected a
                    considerable improvement in Russian-Japanese relations and a cessation of
                    provocative border incidents.</p>
                <p>Dr. Yen, Chinese Ambassador, commenting on the Japanese elections said that while
                    he was sure they would produce no fundamental change in Japan’s attitude toward
                    China they might produce a more suave method of procedure.</p>
                <p>Yen expects to leave Moscow for China about March 20th.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
